  "text": "Django session key rotation audit findings:\n\n1. CYCLE_KEY IMPLEMENTATION: Found in django/contrib/sessions/backends/base.py, class SessionBase, method cycle_key() (lines 428-437). This method is called during login to rotate session keys. It reads the current session data, calls create() to generate a new session with a new key, restores the session data, and deletes the old session key.\n\n2. SESSION BACKEND BASE CLASS: Found in django/contrib/sessions/backends/base.py, class SessionBase. Defines abstract create() method (lines 463-471) and _get_new_session_key() method (lines 194-199). The _get_new_session_key() generates random 32-character session keys and checks existence via self.exists() in a loop until finding an unused key.\n\n3. DATABASE BACKEND IMPLEMENTATION: Found in django/contrib/sessions/backends/db.py, class SessionStore. The create() method (lines 68-79) implements a retry loop that calls _get_new_session_key() and attempts to save via save(must_create=True). The save() method (lines 114-137) performs the actual database INSERT using force_insert=True with a transaction wrapper.\n\n4. COLLISION HANDLING ANALYSIS: YES, collision handling exists through IntegrityError detection. The Session model in base_session.py defines session_key as a PRIMARY KEY (line 28), enforcing database-level uniqueness. When save() encounters an IntegrityError during force_insert (lines 130-132), it raises CreateError, which the create() method catches and retries (lines 75-77). Importantly, collisions do NOT silently overwrite - they are detected and the entire key generation/save process retries.\n\nCONCURRENCY SAFETY ISSUE: The session key rotation has a Time-of-Check-Time-of-Use (TOCTOU) vulnerability. While _get_new_session_key() checks if a key exists before insertion, this check and the subsequent INSERT are not atomic. However, the database PRIMARY KEY constraint provides protection by detecting collisions at the database level and raising IntegrityError, which triggers a retry. The broader concurrency issue in cycle_key() is a potential race condition where concurrent requests could modify session data between when cycle_key() reads the data and when it creates the new session, potentially causing data loss."
}

